<subsection xml:id="subsec-Interpretation-of-pie-charts">
        <title>Interpretation of pie charts</title>
        <activity>
            <p>
                Work in groups
            </p>
            <p>
                (i) Consider the pie chart representing different types of crops planted in a 6 hectare farm shown.
            </p>
            <image>
            <latex-image>
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                    % Define the radius of the pie chart
                    \def\pieRadius{3cm}

                    % Segment 1: Millet (120 degrees)
                    \fill[blue!60] (0,0) -- (0:\pieRadius) arc[start angle=0, end angle=120, radius=\pieRadius] -- cycle;
                    \node[text width=3cm, align=center] at (60:2.2cm) {\textbf{Millet}\\120°};

                    % Segment 2: Potatoes (30 degrees)
                    \fill[red!60] (0,0) -- (120:\pieRadius) arc[start angle=120, end angle=150, radius=\pieRadius] -- cycle;
                    \node[text width=3cm, align=center] at (135:2cm) {\textbf{Rice}\\30°};

                    % Segment 3: Maize (150 degrees)
                    \fill[green!60] (0,0) -- (150:\pieRadius) arc[start angle=150, end angle=300, radius=\pieRadius] -- cycle;
                    \node[text width=3cm, align=center] at (225:2.2cm) {\textbf{Maize}\\150°};

                    % Segment 4: Beans (60 degrees)
                    \fill[yellow!60] (0,0) -- (300:\pieRadius) arc[start angle=300, end angle=360, radius=\pieRadius] -- cycle;
                    \node[text width=3cm, align=center] at (330:2.2cm) {\textbf{Beans}\\60°};

                    % Optional: Add a title below the pie chart
                    \node[below] at (0,-3.8) {\Large Pie Chart representing different types of Crop };
                    
                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image> 
            </image>
            <p>
                (ii) Find and record the information represented in the pie chart.
            </p>
            <p>
                (iii) Discuss and share with other groups.
            </p>
        </activity>
        
        <p>
            Learning point
        </p>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Information represented in a pie chart is obtained using the total number of items represented and the angles expressed as fractions of <m>360^\circ</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <example>
          <statement>
            <p>
                The pie chart shows types of vehicles that passed by a school gate within one hour.
            </p>
            <image>
            <latex-image>
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                   % Define the radius of the pie chart
                   \def\pieRadius{3cm}

                   % Segment 1: Cars (150 degrees)
                   \fill[blue!60] (0,0) -- (0:\pieRadius) arc[start angle=0, end angle=150, radius=\pieRadius] -- cycle;
                   \node[text width=3cm, align=center] at (75:2.2cm) {\textbf{Cars}\\150°};

                   % Segment 2: Lorries (120 degrees)
                   \fill[red!60] (0,0) -- (150:\pieRadius) arc[start angle=150, end angle=270, radius=\pieRadius] -- cycle;
                   \node[text width=3cm, align=center] at (195:2.2cm) {\textbf{Lorries}\\120°};

                   % Segment 3: Pickups (90 degrees)
                   \fill[green!60] (0,0) -- (270:\pieRadius) arc[start angle=270, end angle=360, radius=\pieRadius] -- cycle;
                   \node[text width=3cm, align=center] at (315:2.2cm) {\textbf{Pickups}\\90°};

                   % Optional: Add a title below the pie chart
                   \node[below] at (0,-3.8) {\Large Pie Chart representing types of vehicles};
                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
            </image>
            <p>
                If the number of vehicles that passed by the school were 72, find how many lorries, pickups and cars passed by the school gate.
            </p>
          </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    The number of lorries were <m>\frac{120^\circ }{360^\circ }\times 72=24</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    The number of pick ups were <m>\frac{90^\circ }{360^\circ }\times 72=18</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    The number of cars were <m>\frac{150^\circ }{360^\circ }\times 72=30</m>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>
        <example>
          <statement>
            <p>
                The pie chart below represents careers that <m>56</m> learners would love to pursue in future.
            </p>
            <image>
                <latex-image>
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                      % Define the radius of the pie chart
                      \def\pieRadius{3cm}

                      % Segment 1: Medicine (135 degrees)
                      \fill[blue!60] (0,0) -- (0:\pieRadius) arc[start angle=0, end angle=135, radius=\pieRadius] -- cycle;
                      \node[text width=2.5cm, align=center] at (67.5:1.5cm) {\textbf{Medicine}\\135°};

                      % Segment 2: Fine Art (45 degrees)
                      \fill[red!60] (0,0) -- (135:\pieRadius) arc[start angle=135, end angle=180, radius=\pieRadius] -- cycle;
                      \node[text width=2.5cm, align=center] at (157.5:1.5cm) {\textbf{Fine Art}\\45°};

                      % Segment 3: Teaching (45 degrees)
                      \fill[green!60] (0,0) -- (180:\pieRadius) arc[start angle=180, end angle=225, radius=\pieRadius] -- cycle;
                      \node[text width=2.5cm, align=center] at (202.5:1.5cm) {\textbf{Teaching}\\45°};

                      % Segment 4: Law (90 degrees)
                      \fill[orange!60] (0,0) -- (225:\pieRadius) arc[start angle=225, end angle=315, radius=\pieRadius] -- cycle;
                      \node[text width=2.5cm, align=center] at (270:1.5cm) {\textbf{Law}\\90°};

                      % Segment 5: Engineering (45 degrees)
                      \fill[purple!60] (0,0) -- (315:\pieRadius) arc[start angle=315, end angle=360, radius=\pieRadius] -- cycle;
                      \node[text width=2.5cm, align=center] at (337.5:1.5cm) {\textbf{Engineering}\\45°};

                      % Optional: Add a title below the pie chart
                      \node[below] at (0,-3.8) {\Large Pie Chart representing fields of study};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image>
            <p>
                (a) How many learners want to pursue Law?
            </p>
            <p>
                (b) How many learners want to pursue Fine Art?
            </p>
            <p>
                (c) How many learners want to pursue Medicine?
            </p>
            <p>
                (d) How many learners want to pursue Teaching?
            </p>
          </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    Measure the angle representing each career.
                </p>
                <p>
                    (a) Number of learners who want to pursue Law is <m>\frac{90^\circ }{360^\circ }\times 56=14</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    (b) Number of learners who want to pursue Fine Art is <m>\frac{45^\circ }{360^\circ }\times 56=7</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    (c) Number of learners who want to pursue Medicine is <m>\frac{135^\circ }{360^\circ }\times 56=21</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    (d) Number of learners who want to pursue Teaching is <m>\frac{45^\circ }{360^\circ }\times 56=7</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Number of learners who prefer Medicine to Teaching is  <m>21-7=14</m>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>
    </subsection>